# FlowGuard — Live AI Incident Seeding Plan

## Context

The incident dashboard was built last session with full CRUD but all data was either static (12 hardcoded seed records) or manually entered by FM staff. The AI service (`ai-service/main.py`) already fires unattended-object alerts to the Node server's `/api/detection-alerts` route, which saves to the `DetectionAlert` model — but those alerts never cross over to `IncidentLog`, so they never appear in the dashboard.

This session: bridge the AI alert pipeline into `IncidentLog`, remove all placeholder seed code, add background polling so new AI incidents appear on the dashboard live (with slide-in animation), and add a small AI vs Manual count display.

---

## Files Modified

| File | Change summary |
|---|---|
| `server/routes/detectionAlerts.js` | Bridge: after saving DetectionAlert, fire-and-forget create IncidentLog |
| `client/src/pages/IncidentDashboard.jsx` | Remove seed, add polling, `newRowId` → `newRowIds` Set, add sourceCounts |
| `client/src/css/IncidentDashboard.css` | Add styles for `.inc-source-counter` and chip variants |

No other files touched.

---

## Step 1 — Server Bridge (`server/routes/detectionAlerts.js`)

**Add `IncidentLog` to the require on line 3:**
```js
const { DetectionAlert, IncidentLog } = require('../models');
```

**Add a severity helper before the router definition:**
```js
function severityFromDuration(seconds) {
  if (!seconds || seconds < 120) return 'Low';
  if (seconds < 300) return 'Medium';
  if (seconds < 600) return 'High';
  return 'Critical';
}
```

**Inside `router.post('/')`, after `res.status(201).json(alert)`, add a fire-and-forget bridge:**
```js
// Bridge to IncidentLog — fire-and-forget so AI always gets its 201
IncidentLog.create({
  camera_location: camera_location,
  status: 'UNATTENDED_OBJECT',
  source: 'Object Detection',
  severity: severityFromDuration(duration_seconds),
  person_name: (person_name && person_name !== 'UNKNOWN') ? person_name : null,
  confidence_score: null,
  resolutionStatus: 'Active',
  notes: zone_name ? `[Object Detection] Zone: ${zone_name}` : ''
}).catch(err =>
  console.error(`[Bridge] DetectionAlert id=${alert.id} — IncidentLog create failed:`, err.message)
);
```

**Field mapping:**
| DetectionAlert payload | IncidentLog field | Logic |
|---|---|---|
| `camera_location` | `camera_location` | direct |
| always `UNATTENDED_OBJECT` | `status` | hardcoded (AI only fires on unattended objects) |
| `"Object Detection"` | `source` | hardcoded |
| `duration_seconds` | `severity` | via `severityFromDuration` |
| `person_name` | `person_name` | null if missing or `"UNKNOWN"` |
| — | `confidence_score` | always `null` |
| `"Active"` | `resolutionStatus` | hardcoded |
| `zone_name` | `notes` | `"[Object Detection] Zone: {zone_name}"` |

---

## Step 2 — Remove Static Seed (`IncidentDashboard.jsx`)

**Delete entirely (lines 12–138 of current file):**
- `const T = (hoursAgo) => ...`
- The entire `STATIC_INCIDENTS` array
- `const SEED_FLAG = 'flowguard_incidents_seeded'`

**Replace the mount `useEffect` (current `seedAndFetch` block):**
```js
// Before (lines 289–313): wraps fetchIncidents inside seedAndFetch
// After:
useEffect(() => {
  fetchIncidents();
}, [fetchIncidents]);
```

**Add `silent` flag to `fetchIncidents`** so background polling doesn't trigger the loading bar:
```js
const fetchIncidents = useCallback(async (silent = false) => {
  if (!silent) setLoading(true);
  try {
    const res = await axios.get('/api/incident', {
      headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${getToken()}` },
    });
    setIncidents(Array.isArray(res.data) ? res.data : []);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('Failed to fetch incidents:', err);
    if (!silent) showToast('Failed to load incidents from server.', 'error');
  } finally {
    if (!silent) setLoading(false);
  }
}, [showToast]);
```

---

## Step 3 — Multi-Row Animation: `newRowId` → `newRowIds`

**State declaration:**
```js
// Remove:
const [newRowId, setNewRowId] = useState(null);
// Add:
const [newRowIds, setNewRowIds] = useState(new Set());
```

**`handleCreate` update** (the single-row create action):
```js
// Remove:
setNewRowId(res.data.id);
setTimeout(() => setNewRowId(null), 700);
// Add:
setNewRowIds(prev => new Set([...prev, res.data.id]));
setTimeout(() => {
  setNewRowIds(prev => { const n = new Set(prev); n.delete(res.data.id); return n; });
}, 700);
```

**Row class update** (in the table map):
```js
const rowClass = [
  newRowIds.has(incident.id)       ? 'inc-row-new'      : '',
  incident.id === deletingId       ? 'inc-row-deleting'  : '',
  incident.source === 'Manual'     ? 'inc-row-manual'    : '',
].filter(Boolean).join(' ');
```

---

## Step 4 — Background Polling

**Add `pollForNewIncidents` callback** (after `fetchIncidents`):
```js
const pollForNewIncidents = useCallback(async () => {
  try {
    const res = await axios.get('/api/incident', {
      headers: { Authorization: `Bearer ${getToken()}` },
    });
    const freshData = Array.isArray(res.data) ? res.data : [];

    setIncidents(prev => {
      const existingIds = new Set(prev.map(i => i.id));
      const brandNew = freshData.filter(i => !existingIds.has(i.id));

      if (brandNew.length === 0) return prev; // no change, skip re-render

      const newIdSet = new Set(brandNew.map(i => i.id));
      setNewRowIds(cur => new Set([...cur, ...newIdSet]));
      setTimeout(() => {
        setNewRowIds(cur => {
          const n = new Set(cur);
          newIdSet.forEach(id => n.delete(id));
          return n;
        });
      }, 700);

      return freshData;
    });
  } catch {
    // silent — polling errors not surfaced to user
  }
}, []); // empty deps: uses functional updater to avoid stale closures
```

**Why stale closures are avoided:** The `setIncidents(prev => ...)` functional form receives the current committed state as `prev` at execution time, regardless of when the closure was captured. The poll never reads `incidents` from its scope — it reads `prev` inside the updater.

**Add polling `useEffect`** (after the mount effect):
```js
useEffect(() => {
  const id = setInterval(pollForNewIncidents, 10_000);
  return () => clearInterval(id);
}, [pollForNewIncidents]);
```

---

## Step 5 — AI vs Manual Source Counter

**Add `sourceCounts` memo** (with the other `useMemo` blocks):
```js
const sourceCounts = useMemo(() => ({
  ai:     incidents.filter(i => i.source !== 'Manual').length,
  manual: incidents.filter(i => i.source === 'Manual').length,
}), [incidents]);
```

Uses `incidents` (full list), not `filtered` — counts should reflect total system state regardless of active filters.

**Add JSX** between the closing `</div>` of `inc-stats-grid` and the loading bar:
```jsx
{/* ---- Source Counter ---- */}
<div className="inc-source-counter">
  <span className="inc-source-chip inc-source-chip-ai">AI Detected: {sourceCounts.ai}</span>
  <span className="inc-source-chip-divider">|</span>
  <span className="inc-source-chip inc-source-chip-manual">Manually Logged: {sourceCounts.manual}</span>
</div>
```

**Add to `IncidentDashboard.css`:**
```css
/* --- AI vs Manual source counter --- */
.inc-source-counter {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 10px;
  margin-bottom: 16px;
}

.inc-source-chip {
  display: inline-flex;
  align-items: center;
  padding: 4px 12px;
  border-radius: 999px;
  font-size: 0.75rem;
  font-weight: 700;
  letter-spacing: 0.04em;
  white-space: nowrap;
  border: 1px solid;
}

.inc-source-chip-ai {
  background: rgba(192, 132, 252, 0.10);
  color: #c084fc;
  border-color: rgba(192, 132, 252, 0.25);
}

.inc-source-chip-manual {
  background: rgba(148, 163, 184, 0.09);
  color: #94a3b8;
  border-color: rgba(148, 163, 184, 0.20);
}

.inc-source-chip-divider {
  color: #334155;
  font-size: 0.85rem;
  user-select: none;
}
```

The AI chip reuses the existing `inc-source-od` purple palette (`#c084fc`) — visual language is consistent with the existing OD source badge.

---

## Verification

1. **Server bridge**: POST to `/api/detection-alerts` with `{ zone_name: "Zone A", camera_location: "Test Cam", object_class: "backpack", duration_seconds: 350, person_name: null }` — verify a new row appears in `incident_logs` table with `status=UNATTENDED_OBJECT`, `source=Object Detection`, `severity=High`.
2. **Seed removal**: Clear `localStorage` key `flowguard_incidents_seeded` in browser devtools, hard-refresh — dashboard should show only real DB data, no seed calls in Network tab.
3. **Polling**: Open Network tab in devtools, wait 10s — `GET /api/incident` fires silently, no loading bar appears.
4. **Live animation**: While on the dashboard, use a second browser tab to POST a new detection alert to the server (or curl). Within 10s, the new row slides in with the `inc-row-new` animation.
5. **Source counter**: Create a manual incident and verify "Manually Logged" count increments. After a bridge-created incident appears, verify "AI Detected" count increments.

---

## Notes on Existing Placeholder Data

The 12 seeded incidents already in the DB will remain — they can be bulk-deleted through the existing dashboard Delete buttons, or left to age naturally. The seed code will no longer run going forward. Do not add a DB-wipe mechanism (out of scope).

